An Analysis of Harmful Fuel Type Gas Emissions, Peer Review

Reviewed by Breton Shindel

Source: This data is derived from the US Department of Energy, Fuel Economy Web Services. Fuel economy data are the result of vehicle testing done at the Environmental Protection Agency's National Vehicle and Fuel Emissions Laboratory in Ann Arbor, Michigan, and by vehicle manufacturers with oversight by EPA. This dataset details the vehicle fuel enconomy from the year of 1984 to 2016.

Summarization of the Report¶

An Analysis of Harmful Fuel Type Gas Emissions is a report that takes the audience onto the front lines of industrial efficiency, and environmental and human health stewardship. The report hypothesises that FuelType1 vehicles have a higher frequency of Co2 emmision than FuelType2 vehicles (FuelType1 being the dominant, fossil fuel group, FuelType2 consisting of more alternative fuels). The report defines FuelType1 and FuelType2 as follows:

  • FuelType1"For single fuel vehicles, this will be the only fuel. For dual fuel vehicles, this will be the conventional fuel."
  • FuelType2 - For dual fuel vehicles, this will be the alternative fuel (e.g. E85, Electricity, CNG, LPG). For single fuel vehicles, this field is not used

Each observation shows the details of a vehicle type and what types of fuel it consumes, how long charging takes, model details and more. The data appears to be merged with another dataset that provides information on general trends such as annual consumption of petrolium for the corresponding fuel type.

If the the hypothesis of the report is accepted, we will have strong reason to believe that alternative fuels contribute less to CO2 emissions, thereby signaling an improvement in human and evironmental wellbeing by shifting industry to invest in FuelType2 vehicles. The report continues on to detail the specifications of alternative fuels found in FuelType2, visualize consumption of fuel types, prices of fuel types, combined miles per gallon per fuel and CO2 emissions per fuel type, and model the emission frequencies for vehicles.

In my review, I will focus on other effective ways to visualize and model the data and identify areas in the report that require further investigation into their findings.

Findings¶

Examining the distributions of our data can give us a good idea whether or not our data is related, as well as giving us some warning signs about the data we're using. For instance, CO2 tailpipe emissions show a flat distribution with the highest density at 0, telling us that the majority of vehicles of both fuel types emit 0 emissions! This must be a significant inaccuracy in our data, and we will see later in the review that tailpipe emissions data will fail to provide us with a robust understanding of the differences of emissions between the two vehicle fuel types.

I also notice there is a trend of seeing normal distributions for fuel type 1 data, while fuel type 2 data spikes at 0 for most of its observations. Later in the review we will see that this is because fuel type 2 data is not seperated from fuel type 1 data, therefore there is a significantly high number of features that represent fuel type 2 data with 0s. If not addressed appropriately, the data will skew the visualizations and analyses to be done.

The report by my collegues provides a good start by identifying the lack of normality of the CO2 tailpipe emission data, and the repeating values in it. My review's aim is to expand the examination of normality onto more features, and to indentify how some distributions not being normal translates into issues with out dataset.

From here on I will also highlight the conventional fuel type 2 in red, and the alternative fuel type 2 in blue, to reflect the report's hypothesis that fuel type 2 contributes less to CO2 emissions and fuel type 1.

In [117]:

Unlike my collegues, I choose not to show a normalized plot of the data. The reason I like this plot a little better than the normalized plot is because this plot is simply more accurate to reality, from the reader's perspective. A normalized plot can be very useful, particularly when dealing with features that show barely any noticeable change to the human eye. But it often distorts reality. Here we can see plainly that consumption for barrels of fuel type 1 is steadily decreasing, while there is a small but significant uptick in consumption for barrels of fuel type 2.

There is another way of making this time series plot more powerful. Let's take a look.

Ah, the plot is a little different this time, particularly for Fuel Type 2. This is likely due to the issue we found from the normality plots above: Fuel type 2 data is overrepresented by being given a value of 0, therefore we fixed this by creating a new dataframe that removed the 0 values for both fuel types. Unfortunately, this may create a different type of skewing in our data, and furthermore, the reported data may still be fairly inaccurate.

Price of Fuel Types¶

Next we examine the way price changes with each fuel type. My collegues state that cost for fuel type 2 vehicles is far lower than that of fuel type 1 vehicles. Let's see for ourselves if this will hold true.

Does something feel off about this plot? If alternative fuel costs were that low, it would be so ground breaking that we'd all be switching over to alternative fuels immediately. There must be something going on with this data that's skewing the results.

Looking back at the normalized data, remember that the majority of the values for the cost of type 2 fuel is 0. There must be many 0 values in fuel type 2 that is skewing the data. Let's rework our pivoted table of fuel type 2 data and see if we can get a more accurate reading of its true cost.

In [189]:

Fuel2Price_Data = Data[Data.fuelCostA08 > 0]
In [191]:

plt.plot(co2ACost_Year, color='blue')

plt.title('Average Price for Fuel Types')

plt.show();

The change is as clear as night and data. My collegues were working with a heavily skewed dataset, and the values were so far off that alternative fuels appeared to cost virtually nothing. The reality couldn't be further from the truth.

This makes sense because alternative fuels are so new to our economy. As the years move forward, we are finding increasing innovations to bring the cost of alternative fuels down, making it more competitive with fossil fuels. This peer review reflects that change in our economy, while also showing that th dominant fuel types as well continue to drop in price.

These visualizations are showing us something counterintuitive. As price goes down, so does consumption, for both fuel types. Why would this be? As a former business student, I know all too well that the energy market does not behave normally (many thanks to OPEC and the corporate oligarchy that controls the energy industry). However, the data conveyed by these visualizations show us a significant positive relationship between price and consumption (as price goes up, so too does consumption). This should not be happening. Perhaps the dataset is faulty, or perhaps there's more going on to this data than meets the eye.

CO2 Emissions¶

Finally we're getting to the core of my collegues' report. The visualizations by my collegues suggested that alternative fuels have far fewer emissions than type 1 fuels. However, my collegues later rport that the CO2 data is heavily skewed by -1 values for most observations. We will follow my collegues' steps and see if we can make anything useful out of this data feature.

As the previous report rightfully pointed out, there appears to be an issue with the way the data is reporting co2 emissions. Going through the datset, we find that most values for both co2 and co2A are -1 (each observation, vehicle model, is procuding less than 0 carbon emissions from its tailpipe). This is a clear inaccuracy, and unfortunately will damage the validity of our report's conclusions.

In [226]:

Removing all co2 and co2A values that fall <= 0 will not help us in visualizing the difference between fuel types. The first issue is that it will effectively remove data from all the yesrs up to 2011, and therefore we will not have enough data to make an accurate claim. The next issue is that some Fuel Type 2 vehicals may produce 0 tailpipe emissions, and removing those from our visualized data will effectively skew our visualization and analysis into something inaccurate. My collegue's report seemed to be right to discontinue its visual analysis into carbon emissions of the two fuel types because the data appears to be too inaccurate to work with. Soon, we will fit models onto the CO2 data and evaluate their findings.

Combine Transformers and Estimators in a Pipeline¶

Many learning algorithms require input features on the same scale of optimal performance, so we need to standardize the columns of the dataset before we feed them to a linear classifier. Furthermore, if we want to compress our data into a lower dimensional subspace via Principal Component Analysis (PCA), rather than going through the fitting and transformation steps before, we can chain the standard scalar PCA and Logistic Regression objects in a pipeline:

In [80]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline

pipe_lr = Pipeline([('scl', StandardScaler()), ('pca', PCA(n_components=2)),
                    ('clf', LogisticRegression(random_state=1))])
pipe_lr.fit(X_train, y_train)
print('Test Accuracy: %.3f' % pipe_lr.score(X_test, y_test))

Test Accuracy: 0.979

Pretty high accuracy, right? Unfortunately we can't accept this accuracy score to reflect a real model at face value. We need to account for a bias-variance tradeoff that will occur when modelling unseen data. If we model a learning curve to our data, we can create a visualization to estimate the difference between our model's accuracy with the training set, and its accuracy with an unseen validation set. Furthermore, it will also show us the difference between accuracies as samples increase.

In [84]:
from sklearn.learning_curve import learning_curve

pipe_lr = Pipeline([
        ('scl', StandardScaler()),
        ('clf', LogisticRegression(penalty='l2', random_state=0))])
train_sizes, train_scores, test_scores = learning_curve(estimator = pipe_lr, X = X_train, y = y_train,
                                                        train_sizes = np.linspace(0.1, 1, 10), cv = 10, n_jobs = 1)
train_mean = np.mean(train_scores, axis=1)
train_std = np.std(train_scores, axis=1)
test_mean = np.mean(test_scores, axis=1)
test_std = np.std(test_scores, axis=1)

plt.plot(train_sizes, train_mean, color='blue', marker='o', markersize=5, label='training accuracy')
plt.fill_between(train_sizes, train_mean + train_std, train_mean - train_std, alpha=0.15, color='blue')
plt.plot(train_sizes, test_mean, color='green', linestyle='--', marker='s', markersize=5, label='validation accuracy')
plt.fill_between(train_sizes, test_mean + test_std, test_mean - test_std, alpha=0.15, color='green')

plt.xlabel('Number of training samples')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.legend(loc="lower right")
plt.ylim([0.95, 1.0])
plt.show()

Our estimation gives us excellent news: the model's predictions should be nearly the same between its test predictions and validation predictions. The high accuracy level and low difference between data type predictions indicates that my collegues' model does not suffer from either high variance or high bias.

Next let's implement a validation curve visualization to evaluate the ideal inverse regularization level (C) for our logistic model. My collegues set C at 18. My evaluation will determine if the level appears to be arbitrary, or if my collegues found the optimal level to set the model's inverse regularization strength.

In [86]:
from sklearn.learning_curve import validation_curve

param_range = [0.001, 0.01, 0.01, 1.0, 10.0, 100.0]
train_scores, test_scores = validation_curve(estimator = pipe_lr, X = X_train, y = y_train, param_name = 'clf__C',
                                             param_range = param_range, cv = 10)
train_mean = np.mean(train_scores, axis=1)
train_std = np.std(train_scores, axis=1)
test_mean = np.mean(test_scores, axis=1)
test_std = np.std(test_scores, axis=1)

plt.plot(param_range, train_mean, color='blue', marker='o', markersize=5, label='training accuracy')
plt.fill_between(param_range, train_mean + train_std, train_mean - train_std, alpha = 0.15, color='blue', )
plt.plot(param_range, test_mean, linestyle='--', color='green', marker='s', markersize=5, label='validation accuracy')
plt.fill_between(param_range, test_mean + test_std, test_mean - test_std, alpha=0.15, color='green')

plt.xscale('log')
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.xlabel('parameter C')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.ylim([0.9, 1])
plt.show()

The inverse regulatization appears to barely show any difference between accuracy in the training or validation sets. Furthermore, as C increases, our accuracy improves and its standard deviation narrows. It appeard to level off between a C of 10 and a C of 100, hence my evaluation concludes that my collegues' model is both accurate, has ideally set hyperparameters, and should work equally well against unseen data.

Conclusions¶

My collegues' report takes us to the beginning of an important discovery of the relationships between fossil and alternative fuels. Their report is successful at giving us an overview of the two fuel types' relationships together, and how the change with different features. It also provides helpful time series visualizations of these relationships and how they change by year. The report also utilizes bar, violin, and jitter plots effectively to convey the differences in data distributions for both fuel types. Finally, they successfully build a logistic model that accurately predicts vehicle types with high CO2 emissions, which is as accurate with unseen data as it is with training data. Some areas where their report falls short pertain to the datasets poorly distributed data, and how it skews their visualizations, and not digging deeper into the relationships to categorical features such as the specific fuel types.

Unfortunately, our collegues could not conclude whether or not their hypothesis that fuel type 1 vehicles prodice more CO2 emissions that fuel type 2 vehicles, due to an inadequate dataset. This peer review cannot further test their hypothesis as well due to the dataset.
